At 07:35 AM 9/10/96 -0700, Robert A Goebel wrote:
>        I am a Frank Schaeffer fan and take no offense. Probably because
>I have somewhat the same abrasive style.  Actually, I don't mean to tick
>people off, I just do!  I am not apologetic or compromising about
>issues, especially the Orthodox Faith and moral issues.
>        It then is no surprise to me, to hear people complain about him.
>I've heard him speak and read his articles and book "Dancing Alone".  I
>think he "hits the nail on the head".  That is, one strong, driving
>force that penetrates into the issue or the person hearing it.  No
>gentle taps, just a hard driven spike.

Bob,
Our mission had an experience with Frank that did not work out well. Quite a
few people came to hear him speak and quite a few people left feeling hurt,
discouraged and judged by his remarks. What Frank says and how he says it
are not atypical for new converts. My problem with him has been that he has
taken his anger and frustration out on the road and shared it with the
world. I remain unconvinced that any good is done by this. The talk he gave
would have been fine in the company of Orthodox only and it is true that
much of what he says needs to be said. However I have found that we bring
people into Orthodoxy far more effectively by teaching what we believe and
staying away from openly disparaging their beliefs. It may take a little
longer but the truth will win in the end for the seeker. And how do I know
how people felt? My mother came that night to learn more about Orthodoxy.
She was a Roman Catholic. I know how she felt and I know how even other
Orthodox felt. It was not good.
Alice
alice@tiac.net
"A New Commandment I give to You..."
